The first virtual operator is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still need something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be long.
That the Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed it by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming rates regulation, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators sending SMS from abroad will be cheaper than if they were sent from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is an extreme competition in the Czech market.
That is why the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It may be true that for a classic operator with his own network no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Exactly the virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market brought a significant price downturn, which the classic operators also had to react to.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the Britain market, voices were heard both there and here.
It has been demonstrated that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
However, there is no need to look for examples too far away.
In February this year we inform you about the scene of the virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
Only after half a year did this operator get over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking the Penta group is located which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:phone.
The advantage of virtual operators is possible to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, so that they can function effectively, they are sufficient with many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not bear relatively high costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that, however, often conflict with the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Mobile Tesco in Britain offers SMS at least half of the cost of competition.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland, it can also be a good blow to bet on a goal group.
This operator is specifically directed to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a concept like that of Poland could get stuck in our country.
Thus, Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepýký says: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services, it is relatively saturated"
There is no possibility in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic does not seem too hopeful.
It is more about the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
He indirectly ensured that the current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic would not necessarily be inclined towards this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to avoid any potential competition.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition for Phone O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile telephony.
And how much earlier, better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile telephone operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward at the meetings," said the spokesperson of the group, Pavel Kaidl.
Well, then, maybe they're wasting better times.
It seems that, for non-official information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this point we believe that the situation is suitable for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
The spokesperson for T-mobile, Martina Kemrová, in accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project which, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some specific contract that could be studied in such short horizon."
Vodafone directs its attention rather to the fulfilment of the own requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepýký adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this concerns the distribution of expenditure and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the greatest contribution from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a network shared for a fast internet on the mobile."
Offices responsible - with operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition which would lead to a price downturn and thus to a fall in profits.
Then why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull out of the same rope, proof of that is the grip when U:phone came up.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTU was at the time of U:phone's entry into the company T-Mobile.
You can see the public information available on the ČTU website.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "In addition, it is not long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would be for him and, above all, for his large services."
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, this expressed its typical attitude to this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after a contract on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator is concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of the potential stakeholders was not sufficiently interesting for the classical operators," added Kristian Chalupa, of the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
For offices that should represent consumers' interests, it is more than just a consideration, besides that they should note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual operators are normally operating, we can see that their market entry contributed to the lower prices of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market's media and the lower prices are not within the interest of the UOHS.
The truly dramatic shock in all this case is the disunity of the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as the price of petrol in the gas stations as it is clear that it is a work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has not found signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility in their market operations.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is evidently an analysis of relevant markets developed by the ČTU according to which telecommunications is from the point of view of the commercial tender a single market.
In this kind of market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment, it must be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators would come forward in a similar way.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar obstacles.
Loading responsibility in ČTU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which UOHS washes hands in this whole matter.
We've already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act for the extension of ČTU's competence in the field of commercial tenders which was not effective was introduced recently, even when a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
This must be fully known by the representatives of UOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's okay when no one sees
At the same time, unconsciously, something like a pseudovirtual operator continues to work that in Czech mobile telephony networks a few already exist.
They are companies that place their own prices on mobile telephony services which, however, are only part public.
This is usually about companies that are dedicated to multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephony services.
Usually only some elected ones get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the company carrying a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephone operators prohibit such return.
"If cases such as those cited could be found to be infringing under the terms of the contract that could be translated at the end of the collaboration with the society in question," answered Martina Kemrová to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that this kind of activity carried out by mobile telephone operators would not reach people responsible.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above that thousands of customers can be treated.
None of the operators are opposed to this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they achieve nothing negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the true virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepýký warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows for a speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a per cent of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card of your phone is not in your name so they can't absolutely have it as a normal customer of the operators."
This is exactly what ČTU should look like.
In addition, there is a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround their eyes in this kind of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator's entry?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to be desired it should not be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant decline in service prices.
At the same time, in almost all countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried to protect themselves from this eruption.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, service quality problems, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have defended operators but their clients.
Both with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to emerge the first virtual operator and with him they started to emerge more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory body all this happens as if it were a burning key.
For our experience, we cannot fail to feel that the confusion of the attributes in these cases is good for them.
But we won't be disappointed.
If this information between builders is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile market probably starts moving again.
If any of the operators allows any virtual mobile phone operator to enter, it will be difficult for ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the refusal (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
