Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday its 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the world's safest and most effective blood suppliers.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public, which had been seriously weakened by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the public's discontent, the Government of Canada made a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, who wanted to clarify the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not happen again.
While Judge Krever was delaying his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38 per cent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
After much effort has been made to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained the confidence of the public " , he says before proudly claiming that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in the subsequent confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, recalls that " confidence is something extremely fragile " .
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, account of Decary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
So we support one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emerge from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But some years ago, it has been shown beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nuclear acid tests that enable donors to directly detect the presence of the virus and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nuclear acid tests allowed the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period within a period of less than one week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk of certain donors being infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving blood contaminated by HIV.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Thus, since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500,000 blood products each year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I think it is possible today to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concern," says Hema-Québec head.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion that, for example, the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
Hema-Québec must also provide for sufficient supplies in addition to a secure supply.
" The needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Since more aggressive anti-cancer treatments often require injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which in the medium term regroups only 3 per cent of Quebecis eligible for blood donation. "
All persons with good health, aged 18 years and who meet the eligibility criteria, however, may give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On the average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travelled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory covering the needs of hospitals.
Punctuality is very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they age and are no longer able to give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since the present life is very relaxed, we rarely find time to spend an hour to give your blood," laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone inerts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was previously considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of mother cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We celebrated a few weeks ago, the placing in the bank of our thousandth blood sample of the umbilical cord and is expected to extract more than a thousand of these per year.
We should start to propose it for insertions at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary who describes this program of cord blood taking as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this, " since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
