Psychology of the answers: Why do we spend more money?
The participants in the auctions are willing to spend more money and overestimate the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people don't want to lose in skills such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists have tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental substations.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in a auction and as long as it was being examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI) active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called strata located below the brain cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "auto premium" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention against causing an intense reaction of the stratum.
In order to base their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups voted against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members were betting.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of the loss of the auction, the members of the group lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group that played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
So those so far explained the phenomena of the auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so that we now arrive at a third explanation" - established Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
In the world some five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infections in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by the virus.
Symptoms appear to be very common; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis virus depending on the pathogen agent is spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vaginal humour, saliva).
It is recommended for travellers to be protected by a virus A and B vaccine, there are no vaccines against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, it is manifested by a general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appears in the skin and in the white of the eyes the jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last even two to three weeks.
Each year, one million people die from cancer in the world and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people don't know that you're sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition, systematic medical control, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently there are about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can also be detected with routine laboratory control, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to eradicate the virus from the body, so it can be removed from the infection and prevent cancer.
It was the World Hepatitis Day on 30 September, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by the virus and to the importance of its early recognition.
Does it hurt less those who believe in God?
According to a recent study, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the framework of this unique experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and to the same number of atheists, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of the series of studies in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the various departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis took place the following way; they set a chissing instrument at the left hand of the patient, which applied the electrical shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at it in two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of the 17th century Sassoferrato and the Lady of the Armor of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers had the hope that the Virgin Mary's show would cause a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a calming effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scan, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that period while observing the painting of the religious theme or the other.
Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected", "they were calm and in their hearts peace reigned."
When they observed the picture of the religious theme, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any such impacting image you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person who feels very positive, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality" - added Wright.
After these great results, there is only one question: what effect would it have on the pain regulation if the faithful Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of her size were shown?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary cast even better results?
