The intelligent car imitates the flight of the ape
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacles sensors in nature?
For example, the one of the apes.
In a surprising project presented at the CEETC in Japan, the abbots gave the starting point for the engineers of Nissan to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic steering system for cars of type BR23C nature simulation, to which the characteristics of the avant-garde were given, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that could exacerbate all collisions.
During the flight each abeyorro creates its own particular oval space that actually looks very much like our safety protective capsule - explained in the Kazuhhiro Doi exhibition, technology director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of the beekeepers who are able to see in all directions in an angle above 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the length measurement system for laser beams.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 metres, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle which is immediately turned into a manoeuvre to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the abrasives changes direction by rotating the wheels to the necessary extent.
The difference in any existing system at the moment, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If it wasn't so, the vehicle robot couldn't react fast enough as to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a blessing is doing to excite other disadvantages.
This process must be carried out in an open and closed eye.
However, unlike the abrasives, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be bidimensionally and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for beekeepers to escape other beekeepers, here they used only as a possibility for the car robot the rotating movement and acceleration plus the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and greater its energy density, which means they have a longer life than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, nor much less the storage capacity.
This device must only process some input signals in each second and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No gigabytes or megabytes are needed.
This is the first step in developing technology to unravel the obstacles immediately, which according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into series-made models within ten years.
Another possibility for your application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to lead the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles that exist on his way.
