Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Statistical Office (CSB).
Export industrial prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
As a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industries increased at least by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The higher price increases occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), due primarily to an increase of 4.6 per cent per month in bags and belts and an increase of 2.5 per cent in footwear.
The highest price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
A price reduction in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electric machinery and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the processing sectors of wood (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
In the rest of the processing industry, there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first of all as a result of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a comparison of a 12-month period - in domestic sales in the processing industry - the higher price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal manufacture sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry, a decisive weight increase of 11 per cent was observed.
A decrease in prices was recorded in the textile industry (2.5 per cent) as well as in the manufacture of electric machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
During the year in the processing industry, prices increased globally by 10.2 per cent.
Electricity prices, gas, heat and water supply exceeded 18.7 per cent of previous year's prices.
In August, among the various domestic trade sectors, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in the energy sector and in the intermediate sectors there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the higher price increases occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8%).
A drop of 6.8 per cent was recorded in consumer goods production branches and 1.4 per cent in investment goods.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The rate of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
