Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris, its host is France, which this year is also the President of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her full message, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, called attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations affecting the Roma children and it is also the greatest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights protection organizations attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of Members in the European Parliament - warned that, in addition to discrimination in employment, the gypsies remain outside the labour market first because of their low level of education.
"Most young gypsies have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, so only a small part can get university diplomas."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Euro MP, it is necessary to raise these issues widely between the gypsies and non gypsies.
As early as school begins a gypsum student, more opportunities will be available to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"The gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must guarantee them the right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - Livia Járóka pointed out.
According to the Euro MP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary in order to speed up the process of school deregulation immediately, so it is essential that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives be properly complied with.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer the gypsum children the opportunity to guarantee the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full-fledged citizens" - Járóka demanded.
The objective of the European Summit on Equal Opportunities organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting, which was held in the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a single forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at the European and national levels of the Member States.
